We have that the golden ratio conjugate is one over the
golden ratio!
!
This is the ratio of the distance from the bottom of the feet
to the navel to the distance from the navel to the top of
the head, a relationship long known to anatomy and
artists. However, in paleontology, the study of the
evolution of life we have the intermembral index, the ratio
of the arm to the legs basically which which says a lot
about the way a vertebrate moves. So for chimpanzees
their arms are longer than their legs so the ratio is larger
than one, and this means they dont depend as much on
their legs for manner of propulsion however, in humans the
ratio is less than one (their legs are longer than their arms)
which means they are bipedal.!
In the course of my research of looking at the articial
intelligence and comparing its physical characteristics to
those of biological life, I have become interested in the
intermembral index and found it is connects both bone,
and carbon (biological life) to silicon and germanium
(articial intelligence). The ratio of articial intelligence
compared to biological life is the ratio in humans, around
0.7.!
This is interesting because over the years I have pieced
together an equation using both the intermembral ratio of
humans which I like to characterize with the square root of
two. Namely at some point I have been writing square root
of two as cosine pi over four. I have been writing the
golden ratio as cosine of pi over 5, and the square root of
three as cosine pi/6. I nd their sum is equal
approximately to the molar mass of water compared to
the molar mass of air as a mixture. That is:!
